W365 (Windows 365)
- Cloud-based SaaS that creates Cloud PCs for users
- Users can access Windows 10/11 from Windows, Mac, iOS, Android
- Provides virtual desktop from Microsoft cloud
Editions
- Business → Small orgs, max 300 seats, simple deployment
- Enterprise → Unlimited seats, Intune + advanced management
- Government → US Govt cloud
- Frontline → 1 license supports upto 3 non-concurrent users
- For Agents → AI agent compute platform
W365 vs AVD
- W365 → Fixed monthly cost, simple management, Microsoft managed
- AVD → Pay-as-you-go, Azure portal management, customer managed
- W365 requires less VDI knowledge
- W365 supports self-service restart/troubleshoot
Cloud PC
- Personal virtual PC in cloud
- 1:1 user relationship
- Accessible from anywhere
- Browser/app access available
Benefits
- Multi-device access
- High-speed cloud performance
- Self-service actions
- Consistent device state
Admin Benefits
- No VPN required
- Easy provisioning
- Region-based policies
- Intune management
- Endpoint monitoring
- MFA + Conditional Access
- RBAC security
- Scalable resources
W365 Business vs Enterprise
Domain Join
- Business: Entra ID Join only, no VNet
- Enterprise: Azure AD Join with/without VNet
Policy
- Business: Intune only
- Enterprise: GPO + Intune
Monitoring
- Business: Not supported
- Enterprise: Endpoint Analytics + health alerts
Troubleshooting
- Business: Not supported
- Enterprise: Intune troubleshooting support
Enterprise Requirements
- Intune Admin
- Windows E3 + Entra ID P1 + W365 license
- Azure subscription (optional for MS hosted network)
- MEM management
- Gallery/custom image support
Provisioning
- Automatic Cloud PC creation after license assignment
- Managed through Intune
- Uses MS hosted network or ANC
- 1 license = 1 Cloud PC
- Provisioning can take upto 2 hrs
Grace Period
- 7-day access after license removal
- Cloud PC deleted if not reassigned
ANC (Azure Network Connection)
- Connects Cloud PCs to customer VNet
- Max 50 ANC per tenant
- Requires Intune/W365 admin role
W365 Frontline
- Cost-saving shared Cloud PC model
- Two modes:
- Dedicated
- Shared
Dedicated Mode
- 1 license → upto 3 Cloud PCs
- Only 1 active session allowed
- Best for shift/part-time workers
- Auto power off after sign-out
Shared Mode
- 1 license → 1 shared Cloud PC
- Data deleted after sign-out
- No concurrency buffer
- Supports Cloud Apps
Concurrency Buffer
- Temporary extra session allowance
- Max 4 times/day for 1 hour
- Excess usage → temporary/permanent block
Cloud Apps
- Deliver apps without full desktop
- Runs on Frontline Shared mode
W365 Business
- Max 300 users
- No provisioning policy needed
- Just assign license
- No Azure subscription needed
Downsides
- No hybrid join
- No custom image
- Limited Intune support
Provisioning States
- Failed
- Provisioning
- Provisioned
- Warning
- Grace Period
- Not Provisioned
Cloud PC Resize
- Upgrade CPU/RAM/Disk
- No reprovision required
- Disk downsize not supported
- GPU resize not supported
Cloud PC Restore
- Point-in-time restore
- Short-term: 4/6/12/16/24 hr
- Long-term: every 7 days
- Manual restore point by admin only
Move Cloud PC
- Move between regions/ANC/MS hosted network
- No reprovision needed
- Old restore points deleted
Reprovision
- Deletes old Cloud PC
- Creates new Cloud PC for same user
- Supported only for Failed/Provisioned state
